article.headline: Hawaii 53, St. Louis 52
article.story: ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Hawaii found a way to win another close one, and Saint Louis lost another heartbreaker. Julian Sensley hit a leaner in the lane with 15.2 seconds to go, topping off a 15-point, 11-rebound game that gave the Rainbow Warriors a 53-52 victory over Saint Louis on Saturday. Reserve Matthew Gipson added 10 points on 4-for-5 shooting for the Rainbow Warriors (4-0), who survived a 14-0 Saint Louis run midway through the second half. Hawaii has won its last two games by a total of three points, also beating Southern Illinois 66-64 on Monday. "Their big-time player made a big-time play at the biggest time of the game," Saint Louis coach Brad Soderberg said. "That's basically what it came down to." Reggie Bryant had a season-best 19 points and Izik Ohanon had a career-best 16 rebounds and 10 points for Saint Louis (1-4), which has lost both of its home games by one point. Ohanon had an open shot from the key with three seconds to go that bounced out, and Tom Frericks missed on a tip with one second left. Ohanon was a secondary option after Bryant couldn't get open. "They got the wrong guy shooting the ball," Hawaii coach Riley Wallace said. "The big guy was the only guy open and if you're going to take a chance, I guess that's the one you'd want to shoot the ball. "Not to put him down or anything like that." Saint Louis lost its home opener to Oral Roberts 55-54 last Saturday. In the Paradise Jam, the Billikens lost in overtime to Austin Peay and by three to Eastern Michigan. "Needless to say, this is another tough pill to swallow," Soderberg said. "The challenge now is to make sure our kids don't doubt themselves, don't doubt the system and that they remain united, and that we keep plugging away." Each team led twice in the final minute. Sensley played 39 minutes, and his basket answered a 15-footer from Bryant with 35 seconds left for Saint Louis. Hawaii had only five fouls in the second half and was able to stop Saint Louis' first possession by fouling point guard Dwayne Polk with six seconds left. Saint Louis also had only five fouls in the second half. "We'd have been in trouble if we'd have missed that shot and they got the ball," Wallace said. Hawaii led by six points early in the second half before Bryant and Vas'Shun Newborne keyed a 14-0 run that put Saint Louis ahead 39-31 with 11:48 to go. Saint Louis led by as many as nine points before Hawaii rallied. Hawaii forced 15 turnovers, 12 in the first half while taking a 27-23 lead. The turnovers helped Hawaii compensate for a 41-29 rebounding deficit. Tom Frericks added nine rebounds for Saint Louis. Ohanon had 10 rebounds in the half, already topping his previous career best of nine. Bryant was 7-for-15 after shooting only 33 percent in the first four games. Wallace, 63, is from nearby Jerseyville, Ill., and about 200 people from his hometown attended the game. "I'm not going to be around this game too much more, so I wanted to come home," Wallace said. "I'm glad they got to see a win."
